solutions.content:
So, for the first one I wanted to give me the extra challenge of not using `long` (more on that later) and so I decided to count from `1` to `n`, get the bits right and religiously add one bit at a time.

To do so I declared a sole support variable `res` in the main scope of the function, and a few more in our main loop:
* `i` will be our main pointer, going from `1` to `n`, as mentioned;
* `j` will take the value of `i` and copy it, just to be disassembled, bit by bit;
* `bits` is going to be our storage for the bits of each number initially stored in `j` - given the maximum input size, we are fine with just `17` bits;
* `pos` is the pointer we will use to work on `bits`, initially set to `0` (first cell).

Now, in our main loop we will:
* assign the value of `i` to `j`, as mentioned;
* extract all the bits and store them in `bits`, with the added convenience of storing them in reverse order;
* we will then reverse all the bits in `bits` into `res`, resetting `pos` to `0` again and at each step updating `res` to be double its previous value modulo `1000000007`, plus the current bit.

Once done, we can return `res` :)

The code, running at around 30% time, with significantly low memory consumption (arrays, what would we do without them?):

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int concatenatedBinary(int n) {
        // support variables
        int res = 0;
        for (int i = 1, j, bits[17], pos = 0; i <= n; i++) {
            j = i;
            // extracting the bits
            while (j) {
                bits[pos++] = j % 2;
                j >>= 1;
            }
            // applying the bits
            while (pos) {
                res = (res * 2) % 1000000007 + bits[--pos];
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

Now, can we do better?

But of course, starting with removing the modulo operation, which is notoriously rather expensive, and changing the solution to this (bumped up to 40%):

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int concatenatedBinary(int n) {
        // support variables
        int res = 0;
        for (int i = 1, j, bits[17], pos = 0; i <= n; i++) {
            j = i;
            // extracting the bits
            while (j) {
                bits[pos++] = j % 2;
                j >>= 1;
            }
            // applying the bits
            while (pos) {
                res <<= 1;
                res = (res > 1000000007 ? res - 1000000007 : res) + bits[--pos];
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

Can we do even better? Sure.

I admit I did not want to go there not to add extra complexity, but we really do not need to store the bit in `bits` if we "read" them from the left, so here is some further optimisation

To do so, we will add an extra support variable, `hasSeenBit`, and in our main loop we will change things a bit and have `j` be our binary pointer (is that even a term? Well, let's pretend it is), being initialised to `1 << bitLmt`, with `bitLmt` expressing the maximum amount of bits we will ever need - for example for `n == 20`, `bitLmt` will be set to `5` (`20` is `10100` in binary representation).

We will, in each loop:
* reset `j` to be `1 << bitLmt` and `hasSeenBit` to be `false`;
* we will then extract each bit with `bool(i & j)`, which in our previous example will give us `1`, `0`, `1`, `0` and `0`, as expected;
* update `hasSeenBit`, so that it will be and stay `true` as soon as the first bit is found;
* once a bit has been found, update `res` with the logic discussed above.

The code, which bumped with this change alone to almost 60%:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int concatenatedBinary(int n) {
        // support variables
        int res = 0;
        bool hasSeenBit;
        for (int i = 1, j, bit, bitLmt = ceil(log2(n)); i <= n; i++) {
            // preparing for a new loop
            j = 1 << 17;
            hasSeenBit = false;
            // extracting the bits
            while (j) {
                // getting the next bit, from the left
                bit = bool(i & j);
                // updating hasSeenBit
                hasSeenBit |= bit;
                // updating res, only after we have found at least a bit
                if (hasSeenBit) {
                    res <<= 1;
                    res = (res > 1000000007 ? res - 1000000007 : res) + bit;
                }
                j >>= 1;
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

And finally the last "cheap" one - computing the length in bits of each number, shifting `res` (a `long`, not to risk overflows) by that amount and applying the same logic with modulo and, this time, the whole number in one go.

The last part in particular - not having to split the number into single bits, had the time jump over 80%:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int concatenatedBinary(int n) {
        // support variables
