Here is the process how you can derive recurrent formula

result(n) = result(n - 1) * 2^binaryDigitsOf(n) + n

where binaryDigitsOf(n) is the number of binary digits needed to write number n. 

i = 1:
1 -> "1" = 1
result is 1

i = 2:
2 -> "1""10" = (110) = (1 10) = 1 * 4 + 2 = result * 2^binaryDigitsOf(2) + 2 = result * 2^binaryDigitsOf(i) + i = 6
result is 6

i = 3:
3 -> "110""11" = (11011) = (110 11) = 6 * 4 + 3 = result * 2^binaryDigitsOf(3) + 3 = result * 2^binaryDigitsOf(i) + i = 27
result is 27

i = 4:
4 -> "11011""100" = (11011100)  = (11011 100) = 27 * 8 + 4 = result * 2^binaryDigitsOf(4) + 4 = result * 2^binaryDigitsOf(i) + i = 220
result is 220

And so on until n. We just need to take care of overflow, because of that we use long instead of int and do modulo operation. At the end we convert it to the int. That's it. Enjoy in code!

```
class Solution {
    public int concatenatedBinary(int n) {

		int MOD = 1_000_000_007;

		long[] powersOf2 = getPowersOf2();

		long result = 0;

		for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
			result = (result * powersOf2[getNumberOfBinaryDigits(i, powersOf2)] + i) % MOD;
		}

		return (int) (result % MOD);
    }

	private int getNumberOfBinaryDigits(int n, long[] powersOf2) {

		for (int i = 1; i < 32; i++) {
			if (powersOf2[i] > n) {
				return i;
			} else if (powersOf2[i] == n) {
				return i + 1;
			}
		}

		return 1000; // never will come here
	}

	private long[] getPowersOf2() {
		long[] powersOf2 = new long[32];

		powersOf2[0] = 1;

		for (int i = 1; i < 32; i++) {
			powersOf2[i] = 2 * powersOf2[i - 1];
		}

		return powersOf2;
	}
}
```

