Understanding: In a **binary represenatation**, **1110** = 14 can be written as: **1100** + **10** = (**11**<<*2*) +  (**10**<<*0*) = *12+2 = 14*.
(All Binary Notation are in Bold.) 
Example:
Lets say n = *3*.
So, concatenation would be: **1 10 11 100**
Each time we concatenate, we left shift our previous number by length of binary representation of that number.
So, at *1*, we have *1*.
At *2*, we have **1** **10**, (**1**<<*2*) + **10** = *4 + 2 = 6*,One left shifts twice to create space for the new number which has *2* bits in it. 
At *3*, similarly, **110** **11**, 6 is left shifted twice, so* 6x2x2 = 24 + 3*(the new number) = *27*.

```
class Solution {
public:
    const int mod = 1e9+7;
    int concatenatedBinary(int n) {
        long ans = 0;
        int length = 0;
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; ++i) {
            //Length increases on each power of two.
            if ((i&(i - 1)) == 0) 
                ++length;
            //Left shift by that length.
            ans = ((ans << length) % mod + i) % mod;
            cout << length << endl;
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

