Since we are concatenating binary numbers from left to right , for every number we have to **left shift our result floor[ log(n)+1]** times and **add our current number** .
```
E.g. Consider 3
res = 0                1 (1)                110 ( 1<<2 (i.e.log(2)+1) + 2)                               11011 ( 110<<2 (i.e. log(3)+1) + 3)  
1 to N                    1                                     2                                               3
```

```
class Solution {
public:
    int log2(int n ){
        int c = 0;
        while(n>1){
          n /=2;
            c++;
        }
        return c;
    }

    int concatenatedBinary(int n) {

        int mod = 1e9+7;
        long long ans = 0;
        for(int i =1;i<=n;i++){

            int a = log2(i)+1; 
            ans = ans << a;
            ans = ans + i;
            if(ans>mod){
                ans = ans%mod;
            }

        }

        return ans%mod;
    }
};
```
**Time Complexity : O(n logn)
Space Complexity : O(1)**

**Note :** This can be easily reduced to **O(n)** if we keep the count of bits from the start of the loop .

