```
/*
    Observation:
    -----------

    Let's see changes for 3(N)
        n     result_dec_value      binary_of_current_n     result_binary_string
        1        1                     1                           1
        2        6                     10                          110
        3        27                    11                          11011

    Here in the above sequence of operations we can clearly observe that
    appending the binary form of current n to an existing resultent binary
    string, will left shift the resultent binary string by the numbers of
    total bits in current n.

    For example:
    -----------
        n -> 1, result_dec_val -> 1, bin(1) -> 1, result_bin -> 1

        n -> 2, result_dec_val -> ?, bin(2) -> 10, result_bin -> 110

        result_dec_val = (prev_result_bin << (total_bits_in_current_n)) + n;

                       = (1 << 2) + 2
                       = 4 + 2
                       = 6

        NOTE: 1. (1 << 2) nothing but -> (2 * 2)
              2. total_bits_in_current_n -> means bits that are
              responsible to represent the value of n.(avoid leading 0 bits)


        so therefore, we can conclude that

        If we have equivalent decemal value for all binaries [1, (n - 1)],
        from that we can evaluate decimal for n by using formula

        decVal(n) = [decVal(n - 1) << (log2(n) + 1)] + n

        here in the above formula : (log2(n) + 1) gives total number bits in n in base 2
        decVal(n - 1) : decimal value calculated so far from binaries of [1, n - 1]

        the formula can be placed inside a for loop & n is replaced by loop variable
        let say i.

*/

class Solution {

    private static final int M = 1_000_000_000 + 7;

    private int log2(int n) {
        return (int)(Math.log10(n) / Math.log10(2)) + 1;
    }

    public int concatenatedBinary(int n) {
        long decVal = 1;
        for(int i = 2; i <= n; i += 1) {
            decVal = ((decVal << log2(i)) % M + i) % M;
        }

        return (int)decVal;
    }
}
```

